{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the impacts of different grazing management strategies on invertebrate and mammal biodiversity in US grasslands within a Mediterranean climate?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the action documents, there is limited evidence specifically for US grasslands within a Mediterranean climate. However, several studies from US grasslands provide relevant evidence on grazing management impacts on invertebrate and mammal biodiversity:\n\nFor invertebrates, studies show mixed effects: Two replicated studies in US grasslands found more invertebrates in sheep-, goat-, or cattle-grazed plots compared to ungrazed plots in some comparisons (Action 1419). However, one replicated, randomized, controlled study found fewer invertebrates in plots with simulated grazing compared to ungrazed plots, though similar numbers of invertebrate species were found (Action 1419). One replicated, randomized, controlled before-and-after study in wet grasslands found more aquatic invertebrate species in continuously grazed plots compared to seasonally grazed plots in some comparisons (Action 1421).\n\nFor mammals, studies demonstrate varied responses: Two replicated, controlled studies in US grasslands found that abundances of some or all rodents were higher or increased more on sheep- or cow-grazed plots compared to ungrazed plots, though some species were less abundant or had lower monthly survival on grazed plots (Action 1419). Four studies examining grazer exclusion found mixed results, with two site comparisons in US grasslands finding more mammal species and higher mammal abundance in areas with cattle or sheep excluded compared to grazed areas in some comparisons (Action 1417).\n\nThe evidence primarily comes from grassland systems, though specific Mediterranean climate conditions are not explicitly addressed in these action documents.",
