{"summary": "For Mediterranean farmland, planting flowers shows evidence of increasing pollinator activity on adjacent crops, with one replicated controlled study from Spain finding more pollinators on coriander flowers next to planted flower strips compared to unplanted field margins (actions 2468, 1406). Flower planting also increased wild bee species and individuals in some comparisons, though results varied for different pollinator groups (action 1406). Implementation studies from Italy and Spain showed that pollinator response to flower strips depended on the number and type of flower species planted, with some species being more attractive than others (actions 2468, 1406).

Planting hedgerows showed different benefits, with studies primarily from the USA (as no Mediterranean-specific hedgerow studies were found) demonstrating increased native bee species richness and crop visitation rates by native bees adjacent to hedgerows, though honey bee and syrphid fly responses were inconsistent (actions 1407, 2515). Hedgerows supported more bee species, syrphid fly species, and specialist bees compared to field edges without hedgerows (actions 1407, 2515). The effectiveness of hedgerows increased with age, with older hedgerows supporting more bee and syrphid fly species than younger ones (actions 1407, 2515).

